  footnotes: []
english:
  title: To Baek-ok, Who Fled the Drinking Party on the Seventh Evening and Returned—A Playful Verse
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Weaver and Herdboy dwell where the Milky Way stands guard—
    a river of stars between them, their gaze grows tender and faint.
    Three hundred sixty days stretch through a single year,
    and save for one brief night, they remain forever alone.

    Baek-ok, you follow in Dongfang Shuo's footsteps,
    having stolen the peaches of immortality to bring them to Oshan.
    In one day and one night, a hundred marks of time pass—
    not a single moment for joy without merriment on the face.

    From the Cheongryeong Pavilion, watching the celestial lovers,
    the jade-adorned beauties swirl in their radiant dance.
    Wine cups circulate, pipes and strings make merry discord,
    the guests press their horses forward in jest and play.

    Yet you alone must follow the example of Duke Zheng—
    whip a lean servant on a weary donkey, fleeing with gravel in mouth!
    Do you not know the Weaver and Herdboy teach only excess?
    They fear even a moment's idle breath might slip away.

    Life's pleasures are endless, their abundance never dwindling—
    yet how hard it is to ward off desire's axe.
    When next you come to add your verse to our record,
    do not dismiss my clumsy words, I beg you—
    keep them close.
  footnotes:
    - Dongfang Shuo was a witty immortal in Chinese legend known for stealing the Queen Mother of the West's peaches of immortality.
    - The Weaver (織女) and Herdboy (牛郎) are the two stars of the Seventh Evening Festival (夕夕), allowed to meet only once yearly across the Milky Way.
    - Duke Zheng's flight refers to an anecdote of hasty escape, here used to mock the guest's sudden departure.
    - The 'axe of nature' (伐性之斧) is a Buddhist metaphor for desires that cut away at one's true nature.
